				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>-Xuthaz- wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I like it, was grouped with a mage last night that refused to not use Rathe's Son.  Made me a very sad panda cus the paladin didn't want to have to move around to stay at min melee range.  I must have lost 80% of my swings constantly backing up to stay at max range.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I find it a common that the MT doesn't stand close enough to rooted mobs and they simply refuse to move closer. Rogues being races like halfling and thus standing very close (because it looks not that close to them), and Warriors being large races standing what looks close but actually isn't.
<br />

<br />
When I play my Tank vs rooted mobs I usually press F9 once to see myself from above. Then I can position myself so close that I in normal view would look "right through" the mob without getting any red messages about not being able to hit my opponent.
<br />

<br />
Switching back and forth from this view usually requires you have set up your "normal" first person view to some hotbutton though, to be able to switch back and forth as needed. Something I guess not all people have done.
<br />

<br />
I think rooting and the proximity aggro is very valuable as long as you can teach people how to use it effectively. (Something I can't do in my average pickup group though, but in those I will use Air/Water.)<br />_________________<br />Disclaimer: English is (obviously) not my native language. Send corrections in PM. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
