				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">why should a monster care if a person is 3 inches closer to him if he hasn't attacked the monster at all? He doesn't when he isn't rooted</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Mebbe I misread this but based on what I read, I will answer. When mobs come into camp while we are fighting, they are all about killing the person that came along and pulled them (or the tank by this point if he isn't the puller). If they get rooted behind me (on my rogue), they turn and start hitting me because their buddy's distress call told them to do it. I am in range and they want to whack something. When mob A dies, we move to rooted mob B and as was said above, rogues are limited by the small range weapons. Most tanks do not understand that by standing in a mob's face close enough to kiss, they can help us not get beat to piss if they did it each time a mob was rooted.
<br />

<br />
Now to finish answering the above quote, if you are not in melee with a mob's buddies and it is rooted, you can likely stand or sit there all day next to it as long as it has someone on it's agro list orther than you. Oft times I will find that if I am in agro range of a mob and a group is fighting, I throw hide/sneak up while it has had ample time to make LoS contact with me (no melee). Group wipes yet the mob does not remember me. Just an observation does not really have anything to do with this hehe. Or does it?...
